<h2 id="qas">Q&amp;As</h2>

<h3 id="calculating-the-concentration-of-110-and-1100-solutions">Calculating the concentration of 1:10 and 1:100 solutions</h3>

<blockquote>
  <p>I think \(V_1\) for stock solutions is 50 mL, but canâ€™t figure out what \(V_1\) is for 1:10 (10 mL ?) and 1:100 dilutions. I want to confirm that \(M_1\) is 1.0 M for all calculations and \(V_2\) is 100 mL. Iâ€™ve looked at the lab procedure and lab video, but get confused about the process of dilutions regarding volumes of \(V_1\).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>As an example, I will walk through the concentration calculations for the  hydrochloric acid dilutions.</p>

<p>The concentration of the stock solution,  \(M_{HCl(1)} = 1.00 \text{ M}\) (letâ€™s use 3 sig. figs.)</p>

<p>where (1) means initial state. Some textbooks use \(i\) to determine initial. Likewise,  we would use (2) or \(f\) to indicate the final state.</p>

<p>First step:</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Dilute the solution 10-fold by using a clean, primed, 10 mL volumetric pipette to add 10.00 mL of the stock acid solution to a 100 mL volumetric flask and filling it to the line with deionized water.</code></p>

<p>This means \(V_{HCl(1)} = 10.00 \text{ mL}\), which is the amount of stock solution</p>

